   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "## Section 5 — Correlation Analysis: Findings\n",
    "\n",
    "### 5.6 Summary of the Correlation Structure\n",
    "\n",
    "The correlation analysis shows that the dataset contains **meaningful local redundancy**, but not a universally collinear numerical space.\n",
    "\n",
    "| Diagnostic | Main Result | Interpretation |\n",
    "|---|---|---|\n",
    "| **Full correlation heatmap** | Dependence is concentrated in visible clusters | Correlation is structured, not pervasive |\n",
    "| **High-correlation thresholding** | Only a limited subset of feature pairs exceeds the cutoff | Redundancy exists, but is localized |\n",
    "| **Economic review of strongest pairs** | Many strong links are financially expected | High correlation is not automatically harmful |\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "### 5.7 What This Means for Feature Selection\n",
    "\n",
    "The correct feature-selection logic is **selective, not mechanical**.\n",
    "\n",
    "1. **Do not drop features purely because correlation is high**\n",
    "   - In accounting data, many strong correlations reflect scale, shared denominators, or accounting identities.\n",
    "\n",
    "2. **Treat near-duplicates differently from conceptually distinct variables**\n",
    "   - If two variables encode almost the same information, pruning is reasonable.\n",
    "   - If they capture different financial mechanisms, keep both until validation shows they are redundant.\n",
    "\n",
    "3. **Adapt the strategy to the model family**\n",
    "   - **Tree-based models:** generally tolerate correlated inputs well.\n",
    "   - **Linear or distance-based models:** more sensitive to redundancy and may require pruning, regularization, or robust feature selection.\n",
    "\n",
    "4. **Use correlation as a pre-screen, not a final verdict**\n",
    "   - Final decisions should combine:\n",
